{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"source": "pdfs/Population-synthesis-using-incomplete-microsample.pdf", "page_numbers": "[6]", "headings": "['4.0.3. Sampling and Structural Zero Evaluation']"}, "page_content": "4.0.3. Sampling and Structural Zero Evaluation\nBased on the definitions provided in Kim and Bansal (2023), we extracted general sample, sampling zero, and structural zero data for each generated population. We carried out this process for the k-joint attribute combination, as detailed in Section 4.0.2, and at various data sampling levels. Figure 2 illustrates the different type of data types and the region of overlaps across different population distribution for calculating general score, sampling rating and structural score. We computed the ratio of both the general sample and sampling zero in the generated population in comparison to the combinations present in the h-population . We determine the ratio of structural zeros by calculating the total number of structural zero instances generated by the WGAN-GP models against all the unique combinations produced by the model itself.", "type": "Document"}}